Challenge #1: Using cd, ls, cat command

Move into the current userâ€™s home directory using the cd command.
List the contents of /etc using the ls command and an absolute path.
Display the contents of /var/log/cloud-init-output.log using the cat command and an absolute path.
Move into the root directory (/) using an absolute path.


Challenge #2: Using the Tail Command

Using the tail command, provide a output of the last 10 lines of the log file located at /var/log/cloud-init-output.log.


Challenge #3: Piping, Grep, Vi, Cat.

Display the contents of /etc/ssh/ssh_config page using the cat command and search for the word "ciphers" using the grep command.
Download the content of this page to your server or local machine.
Edit the downloaded page using vi and replace 'enter-your-name-here' with your name.


Challenge #4: Using the package installer

Become root temporarily in a terminal.
Run the following command as root: yum update && yum install telnet nc httpd
Search for a package named squid in the official repositories and display information about it.
Logout root from the terminal using a keyboard shortcut.


Challenge #5: Create Directory

Using the mkdir commands create the directory names: centos, ubuntu, redhat.
Navigate to each directory using cd and create the files security.txt and updates.txt.
Send a screenshot for each directory.


Bonus:

Install the nginx package web server using yum.
Verify the status of the nginx web server is running.
Remove the web server using yum.
